      "id": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2026/05/260524021151.htm",
      "url": "https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2026/05/260524021151.htm",
      "title": "[ScienceDaily] Common heart drug taken by millions found useless — and possibly dangerous",
      "content_html": "<img src=\"https://www.google.com/s2/favicons?domain=www.sciencedaily.com&amp;sz=128\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\nA massive international study could upend 40 years of heart attack treatment. Researchers found that beta blockers—routinely prescribed after uncomplicated heart attacks—offered no real benefit for patients whose heart function remained normal, despite being given to millions worldwide. Even more surprising, women taking the drugs faced a higher risk of death, repeat heart attack, or hospitalization for heart failure compared to women who didn’t receive them.",
      "date_published": "2026-05-25T12:36:20+00:00",
      "authors": [
